In [11]:
# Performing Univariate Analysis to study the central tendency and dispersion
# Plotting distplot and boxplot to study distribution
def Uni_num(var, figsize=(9, 9)):
    fig, (ax_box, ax_dis) = plt.subplots(
        2, 1, sharex=True, figsize=figsize, gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.35, 0.65)}
    )

    sns.boxplot(var, ax=ax_box, showmeans=True, color="orange")
    sns.distplot(var, ax=ax_dis, kde=True, color="green")
    ax_dis.axvline(np.mean(var), color="m", linewidth=2, linestyle="--")
    ax_dis.axvline(np.median(var), color="black", linewidth=2, linestyle="--")

In [18]:
def Count_uni(feature, figsize=(10, 7)):

    ax = sns.countplot(feature, palette="Set2")
    plt.xticks(fontsize=13)
    total = len(feature)  # length of the column
    for p in ax.patches:
        percentage = "{:.1f}%".format(
            100 * p.get_height() / total
        )  # percentage of each class of the category
        x = p.get_x() + (p.get_width() / 2) - 0.1  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_y() + p.get_height()  # hieght of the plot
        ax.annotate(
            percentage, (x, y), size=12, color="black"
        )  # To annonate the percentage on the barchart

Outlier Detection and Treatment¶

In [32]:
outlier_num = df.select_dtypes(include=np.number)
Q1 = df.quantile(0.25)  # To find the 25th percentile and 75th percentile.
Q3 = df.quantile(0.75)

IQR = Q3 - Q1  # Inter Quantile Range (75th perentile - 25th percentile)

lower = (
    Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
)  # Finding lower and upper bounds for all values. All values outside these bounds are outliers
upper = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
In [33]:
round(((outlier_num < lower) | (outlier_num > upper)).sum() / len(df) * 100, 3)

K-means Clustering¶

In [37]:
clusters = range(1, 11)  # a range of possible K values
meandistortions = []  # empty list for elbow curve plot

for k in clusters:
    model = KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    model.fit(df_scaled_subset)
    model.predict(df_scaled_subset)
    distortion = (
        sum(
            np.min(cdist(df_scaled_subset, model.cluster_centers_, "euclidean"), axis=1)
        )
        / df_scaled_subset.shape[0]
    )
    meandistortions.append(distortion)
    print("Number of Clusters:", k, "\tAverage Distortion:", distortion)

plt.plot(clusters, meandistortions, "bo-")  # Elbow Curve
plt.xlabel("K")
plt.ylabel("Distortion")
plt.title("Elbow method to select optimal K value")

Let's check the silhouette scores

In [40]:
sil_score = []
cluster_list = list(range(2,10))
for n in cluster_list:
    model1 = KMeans(n_clusters=n)
    pred = model1.fit_predict(df_scaled_subset)
    score = silhouette_score(df_scaled_subset,pred)
    sil_score.append(score)
    print('For n_cluster ={}, the silhouette score is{}'.format(n,score))
    
plt.plot(cluster_list,sil_score)
plt.title('Silhouette Method')
plt.xlabel('K')
plt.ylabel('score')

Cluster Insights:¶

Cluster 0

  • There are 386 Customers in this cluster
  • Majority of customers have Avg_Credit_Limit less than \$50000 in this cluseter
  • Customers have between 4 to 7 Credit cards
  • Total_visists_bank is high
  • Total_visits_online is low, between 0 to 3.
  • Total_calls_made is moderate between 1 to 4

Cluster 1

  • There are 224 Customers in this cluster
  • The Average_Credit_Limit is very low and less than \$25000, with few outliers in the high end.
  • Customers have between 1 to 4 credit cards
  • Total_visits_bank is low, between 0-2
  • Total_visits_online is at moderate, as most customers visit between 2-4 times
  • Total_calls_made is the highest for this cluster, with most customers making between 5 to 9 calls to the bank

Cluster 2

  • There are only 50 customers in this cluster
  • The Average_Credit_Limit for this cluster is higer; at \$80000 and above
  • Likewise, most customers have between 8 to 10 credit cards
  • Total_vistits_bank is the lowest here between 0 to 1 for almost all customers
  • Total_visits_online is high here, with most customers visiting between 8 to 13 times
  • Total_calls_made is low, with most customers making less than 2 calls to the bank
